Anonymous Sun 13 Mar 2022 15:48:10 No.46149671 Report
Quoted By: >>46149715
>>46149245
>I kinda expected the author would run into a roadblock
This kinda brings up a sad point I've made before about outlines.
If a story gets too popular, any outline you started with gets kicked in the teeth. This gets exponentially worse if the story is slanted toward the plot-based side of the equation. The readers start telling the writer what they think or want, and ten times out of ten they try to incorporate it.
Now if the story has an overarching plot that doesn't really matter, you can get away with this for a much longer time. The problem becomes keeping your characters consistent in a character-based story. Like a plot-based story, where the actions in Chapter Three impact the events of Chapter Twenty, characters need reasons to feel and do as they will. Can you do it? Yeah, but get ready to write twice as much, or more, to avoid retconning yourself badly. And if you do it too often, then you will cheapen the whole thing.

I've done stuff that's gotten a decent bit of popularity, and it's hell. It's exactly like the feeling of having a micromanaging boss or being forced to work in a committee where having a say is more important than the end result.
I envy people elsewhere that can improvise around their outlines and drafts without giving up their vision. Hell knows that I can't do it, and I suspect that 99% of the delays here are people losing steam because even the slightest nudge to their plans derails their motivation. And since 99% of the writefags here run on motivation instead of discipline, you can see these problems coming a long ways away.

the tl;dr: when it turns into a job, people quit because they have to choose between expectations and their outline

Not the best example, since the words for food and eat are so similar, but luckily Großschreibung saves the day here.

>I eat food
Ich esse Essen.

No change it structure here, but.

>I will eat food.
Ich werde Essen essen.

There's change here.

This brought my attention to something else.
"will" (base form wollen) is the german word for want, it's even pronounced the same way!

So stuff like
>I will go to the park
could be misunderstood to mean
>I want to go to the park.

At least it stumped most students in early english classes.
